# Web Portfolio Project Conventions

## Architecture and scope
- This repo has two apps: `frontend` (Next.js App Router + TypeScript + Prisma) and `backend` (Express ESM JavaScript proxy APIs).
- Keep frontend business/data access in `frontend/lib`, route handlers in `frontend/app/api`, and UI in `frontend/components`.
- Keep backend pattern as `routes -> controllers -> services`; avoid mixing remote API logic directly into routes.

## Frontend coding style
- Use TypeScript with strict typing; avoid `any` and keep exported types explicit for payloads/shared models.
- Keep existing style conventions: single quotes, no semicolons, and `@/` imports for app-local modules.
- For client components, include `'use client'` only when React hooks/browser APIs are required.
- For server actions, include `'use server'` and keep them focused on auth/data mutations.

## Data, auth, and APIs
- Validate request payloads with `zod` in API routes and return clear JSON errors with appropriate status codes.
- Reuse `auth()` from `@/auth` for dashboard-protected routes/pages and keep unauthorized responses consistent.
- Use `prisma` from `@/lib/prisma`; do not instantiate additional Prisma clients.
- When mapping DB records to UI/API models, use dedicated mapper utilities (for example the blog mapping pattern).

## Backend API conventions
- Follow existing backend quote style (`"` strings) and no semicolons.
- Keep controllers defensive: validate query params, handle upstream failures, and return stable JSON shapes.
- Place external API normalization/query parsing in `services`, not in route files.

## Safety and workflow
- Never commit secrets or `.env` files; use environment variables only.
- Do not modify generated/vendor-like UI primitives under `frontend/components/ui` unless explicitly requested.
- Prefer minimal, targeted edits that match existing patterns instead of broad refactors.
